title: Cable Pins
caption: Identified by Philip Konkel MD, Orthopedics and Hand Surgery, Menomonee Falls, WI: ""These are from Zimmer, and are known as cable pins, designed for olecranon Fx and osteotomy repair. The wire is swedged into the pin, and must be cut to remove, (heavy wire cutter). The pins have a hex fitting on the end, and there is a driver that can be chucked into a drill, for insertion and removal. The insertion set from your Zimmer rep has what is needed for removal. One note of advice, the pins when inserted will drive in only so far, the threaded end as it draws into the bone will advance the pin into the bone, but the driver is larger than the hole for the pin, so the pin spins off the driver, stopping its forward progress, so for removal, you need to remove a little bone from around the end of the pin to fit the driver for removal.

title: Zimmer NCB Periarticular Proximal Femoral Plate
caption: 98 yr old frail female patient with periprosthetic fracture above a Zimmer retrograde nail used for lower third shaft fracture within a 12 month period where the options were to revise the nail or to by work around it. Solution:  Zimmer NCB periarticular proximal femoral plate with polyaxial screws allowed to by pass the nail and fix the fracture with additional cable around the plate.

title: Zimmer Retrograde Nail
caption: 98 yr old frail female patient with periprosthetic fracture above a Zimmer retrograde nail used for lower third shaft fracture within a 12 months period where the option was revise the nail or to work around it.  An accompanying image demonstrates the following solution:  Zimmer NCB periarticular proximal femoral plate with polyaxial screws allowed to bypass the nail and fix the fracture with additional cable around the plate.
